<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>RECORD DATE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Only stockholders of record at the
close of business on March&nbsp;7, 2022 are entitled to vote. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>VIRTUAL MEETING </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Annual Meeting will be held in virtual format to protect the health of our stockholders, directors and guests during the continuing
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic and to make the Annual Meeting accessible to all of our stockholders. The virtual Annual Meeting will afford our stockholders the same rights and opportunities as an <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-person</FONT> meeting, allowing for active participation by all of our stockholders at no cost, regardless of their geographic location. To attend the Annual Meeting, vote and submit questions during the Annual Meeting,
go to <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> on the date of the meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>FORM <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT>
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for fiscal year 2021 is enclosed if you received proxy materials by mail. The Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> is accessible on the Internet at <U>www.proxyvote.com</U> if you received the Notice of Internet Availability of Proxy Materials or previously consented to electronic delivery of proxy materials. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; padding-top:12pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Your Vote is Important </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You may vote your shares in one of the following four ways: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><DIV ALIGN="right">

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top">2. By Internet:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">See the instructions at <U>www.proxyvote.com</U>;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top">3. By mail:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">If you received these proxy materials by mail, by signing, dating and mailing the enclosed proxy card; or</TD>

<TD VALIGN="top">4. At the meeting:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Virtually attend our Annual Meeting, where you can submit a vote.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you vote by telephone or Internet, you should have your proxy card, Notice of Internet
Availability of Proxy Materials or voter instruction card in hand when you call or go to <U>www.proxyvote.com</U>. If you hold your shares through a bank or broker that does not offer telephone or Internet voting, please complete and return your
proxy card by mail. If you receive more than one proxy card, Notice of Internet Availability or voter instruction card that has a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number, you must vote each separately to ensure that all
shares you own are voted. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you plan to attend the meeting, you may vote at the Annual Meeting. To do so, you must be a holder of
Illinois Tool Works Inc. shares as of the record date of March&nbsp;7, 2022, and visit <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> on the date of the meeting. You will log into the Annual Meeting by entering your unique <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number found on your proxy card, Notice of Internet Availability or voter instruction card, as applicable. You may log into the Annual Meeting beginning at 8:15 a.m., Central Time, on May&nbsp;6,
2022 and the Annual Meeting will begin promptly at 8:30 a.m., Central Time. As part of the Annual Meeting, we will hold a live question and answer session, during which we intend to answer questions that are submitted in writing during the meeting
by our stockholders who log in with their unique <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number and are pertinent to the Company and the business of the meeting, as time permits. For more information about how to attend the Annual
Meeting online, as a stockholder or as a guest, please see &#147;Other Information&#151;Voting and Virtual Annual Meeting Information&#148; in this proxy statement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Whether or not you plan to virtually attend the meeting, please vote as soon as possible. Under New</B><B></B><B>&nbsp;York Stock
Exchange rules, your broker will NOT be able to vote your shares on Proposals 1, 3 or 4 unless it receives specific instructions from you.</B> If you hold your shares through a bank or brokerage account, we strongly encourage you to return the
voting instruction card to your bank, broker or other holder of record so that your vote is counted. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; padding-bottom:12pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Avoid
escheatment. </B>We have been advised that some states are strictly enforcing unclaimed property laws and requiring shares held in &#147;inactive&#148; accounts to be escheated to the state in which the stockholder was last known to reside.<B> One
way you can show that your account is active is to vote your shares.</B> </P></div> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>IMPORTANT NOTICE REGARDING THE AVAILABILITY OF PROXY MATERIALS FOR THE ANNUAL
MEETING OF STOCKHOLDERS TO BE HELD MAY&nbsp;6, 2022: The Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> and this 2022 Proxy Statement are available on the Company&#146;s website at <U>www.itw.com</U> under the &#147;Investor Relations&#148; link.
Paper copies are available without charge upon written request to the Company at Illinois Tool Works Inc., 155 Harlem Avenue, Glenview, Illinois 60025, Attention: Secretary. </B></P>
</DIV></Center>

skills and attributes do not represent all the knowledge, skills and experience or attributes of our director nominees.</TD></TR>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:7%; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_4"></A>&nbsp;&nbsp;Sustainability and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> Response </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;margin-left:7%;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a; width:86%">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:8%; margin-right:8%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B>Strategy.</B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> Our sustainability strategy is built around a framework that is consistent with our core values and decentralized, entrepreneurial culture. It is
operationalized at the division level and consists of four key elements: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="80%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center"><B>Our&nbsp;Governance<BR>&amp; Ethics</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center"><B>Our People</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center"><B>Our&nbsp;Communities</B></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center"><B>Our&nbsp;Environment</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:8%; margin-right:8%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B>Board Oversight.</B></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> Our Board plays an active role in the Company&#146;s sustainability strategy, including environmental, social and governance (&#147;ESG&#148;) matters. It reviews annually with management the Company&#146;s ESG strategy
and performance. Throughout the year, the Board also receives periodic updates from management regarding progress on ESG strategy and performance, which may include, for example, discussions relating to ESG initiatives, risks and reporting.
Throughout 2021, the Board continued to provide strong oversight to the Company&#146;s response to the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic, including with respect to the health and safety of our workforce as well as commercial
and financial challenges presented. For more information about the Board&#146;s oversight function, see &#147;Board of Directors and its Committees &#151; Board&#146;s Role in Risk Oversight.&#148; </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">2 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B>Management Commitment.</B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL">
The Company&#146;s management team, subject to oversight by our Board, structures, monitors and adjusts the Company&#146;s sustainability efforts in a manner that is consistent with our core values and best serves the interests of the Company and
its stakeholders. Each year, senior management reviews the long-range plans of our segments and divisions. These plans consider, as appropriate, long-term sustainability implications and the ability to meet customer needs related to sustainability
and clean technology. During 2021, the Company&#146;s management continued to respond promptly and decisively to the unprecedented health, safety, commercial and financial challenges brought on by the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT>
pandemic. For more information, see &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; Executive Overview &#151; 2021: Disciplined Execution and Strong Financial Performance in a Challenging Environment.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Recent Developments </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our People; Safety.</I></B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> Since the outbreak of the pandemic in early 2020, the Company&#146;s management determined that its number one priority would be to
protect the health and support the well-being of ITW&#146;s colleagues. With our employees&#146; health and well-being a top priority, we chose to use our strong financial foundation to reinforce our commitment to our people and did not initiate any
enterprise-wide employment reduction mandates or programs in 2020 or 2021. Additionally, we redesigned production processes to ensure proper social distancing practices, adjusted shift schedules and assignments to help colleagues who have child and
elder care needs and implemented aggressive new workplace sanitation practices and a coordinated response to ensure access to personal protective equipment to minimize infection risk. For more information, see &#147;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis &#151; Executive Overview &#151; 2021: Disciplined Execution and Strong Financial Performance in a Challenging Environment.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our People; Diversity and Inclusion.</I></B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> We remain committed to achieving our Diversity and Inclusion (D&amp;I) goals and enhancing the diversity of our
global leadership teams. We have seen significant improvement since beginning our current D&amp;I strategy in 2013. As of December&nbsp;31, 2021, approximately 28&nbsp;percent of our top 1,000 global senior leaders are women and approximately
18&nbsp;percent of our U.S.-based senior leaders are racially or ethnically diverse. In addition, the diversity of our executive leadership team continues to increase, currently including five females, one of whom is Asian-American, and one
African-American male. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our Communities.</I></B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"> In 2021, we
continued to invest in the communities where our colleagues live and work and where we do business. We supported our communities during the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic through
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-kind</FONT> and financial donations. We also continued to empower our colleagues globally to make positive contributions to the organizations that mean the most to them, including through our $3 for $1 corporate
match program in the U.S. and Canada. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our Environment.</I></B></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL">
We continue operating our business in a way that demonstrates our dedication to global environmental sustainability, including continuous improvement in reducing our impact on the environment. In 2019, we announced a greenhouse gas emissions
intensity reduction target and met that target by the end of 2020. In early 2021, we set a new target to reduce by 2030 the combined Scope 1 and Scope 2 greenhouse gas emissions per U.S. dollar of operating revenue by 40&nbsp;percent below 2017
levels. We will report our progress towards achieving the revised target annually in our Sustainability Report. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Sustainability Report, published
annually and available on our website (<U>www.itw.com/sustainability</U>), contains detailed information about our initiatives and progress in each of the four key elements that comprise our sustainability strategy, including our updated greenhouse
gas emissions intensity target and response to <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19.</FONT> Information in the Sustainability Report or on the Company&#146;s website is not incorporated herein by reference. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">3 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_6"></A>Proposal 1 - Election of Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stockholders are being asked to elect the ten director nominees named in this proxy statement at our Annual Meeting. The individuals listed below have been nominated by
the Board of Directors as recommended by the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee. See &#147;Corporate Governance Policies and Practices&#148; for more information regarding our candidate selection process. If elected, each director nominee
will serve until the 2023 Annual Meeting, until a qualified successor director has been elected, or until he or she resigns or is removed. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We will vote your shares
as you specify on the proxy card, by telephone, by Internet or by mail. If you do not specify how you want your shares voted, we will vote them &#147;FOR&#148; the election of all the nominees listed below. If unforeseen circumstances (such as death
or disability) make it necessary for the Board of Directors to substitute another person for any of the nominees, we will vote your shares &#147;FOR&#148; that other person. The Board of Directors does not anticipate that any nominee will be unable
to serve. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Each nominee for director brings a strong and unique background and set of skills to the Board, giving the Board as a whole competence and experience in a
variety of areas. Set forth below is biographical information provided by the nominees, as well as a description of the experiences, qualifications, skills and attributes that led the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and the Board to
conclude that each nominee should serve as a director of the Company. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Daniel J. Brutto</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retired President of</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">UPS International</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">and Senior Vice</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">President of United</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Parcel Service, Inc.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Director since 2012</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:1pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Age: 65</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brutto retired as President of UPS International and Senior Vice
President of United Parcel Service, Inc., a global package delivery, supply chain management and freight forwarding company, having served in these capacities from 2008 to 2013. From 2016 to 2017, he served as Executive Chairman of Radial, Inc., a
global fulfillment, customer care and omnichannel technology company; from 2015 to 2016 he served as Vice Chairman of eBay Enterprise/Innotrac, the predecessor business to Radial, and prior to 2015 he served as a director of Innotrac.
Mr.&nbsp;Brutto had over 38 years of experience at UPS, serving in various areas with increasing levels of responsibility, including global operations, finance, accounting, information systems, mergers and acquisitions, marketing and business
development. His service at UPS included President, Global Freight Forwarding and corporate controller. He has served as a director of ITW since 2012 and currently serves as a director of Sysco Corporation, where he serves as Chairman of the
Corporate Social Responsibility Committee and a member of the Corporate Governance and Nominating and Executive Committees. He has not served as a director of any other publicly traded company in the last five years. In the past, he has served on
the board of the US China Business Council, the Guangdong Economic Council and the Turkey Economic Advisory Council. He was also a delegate to the World Economic Forum, Davos Switzerland, from 2009 to 2013.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Skills and Qualifications:</B></FONT></P>

with a major global company, including the establishment of operations in 35 countries, along with his significant international business experience and board leadership role in the area of Corporate Social Responsibility, bring valuable
perspectives to our Board.</P></TD></TR>

and Latin America. Mr.&nbsp;Griffith has served as a director of ITW since 2012, and previously served as a director of AB Volvo, The Timken Company and Goodrich Corporation. He has not served as a director of any other publicly traded company in

<P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retired Vice Chairman,</P>
<P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Client Service</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">PricewaterhouseCoopers</P>

since 2016</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-bottom:1pt; margin-top:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Age: 66</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Henderson retired as Vice Chairman, Client Service of PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP (PwC), a global professional services firm, in June 2016,
having served in that capacity since 2007. He also served as PwC&#146;s Greater Chicago Market Managing Partner from 2003 to 2013 and, prior thereto, Managing Partner of the Cleveland Office. During his career at PwC, Mr.&nbsp;Henderson gained
significant broad-based experience working with boards and audit committees of Fortune 500 global organizations across multiple markets and industry sectors. Mr.&nbsp;Henderson has been a Certified Public Accountant since 1977. He has served as a
director of ITW since 2016 and currently serves as a director of The J.M. Smucker Company, where he serves as Chairman of the Audit Committee, and Northern Trust Corporation, where he serves as Lead Director, Chairman of the Audit Committee, and a
member of the Capital Governance, Compensation and Benefits, Corporate Governance and Executive Committees. He has not served as a director of any other publicly traded company in the last five years. Mr.&nbsp;Henderson also has significant
expertise as a participating board member of a number of professional, civic and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">not-for-profit</FONT></FONT> organizations.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Skills and Qualifications:</B></FONT></P>

with the boards and audit committees of complex global companies, his other board leadership roles and leadership roles at a major professional services firm, as well as his experience with risk oversight, bring valuable perspectives to our
Board.</P></TD></TR>

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_7"></A>Board of Directors and its Committees </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s Board of Directors met six times during
2021, including at five regularly scheduled meetings and one special meeting. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> directors, all of whom are independent, met five times in regularly scheduled executive sessions in conjunction with
the regular Board meetings. The Company strongly encourages its directors to attend all Board and committee meetings and the Annual Meeting of Stockholders. In 2021, our directors attended 98% of the total number of meetings of our Board and the
respective Committees on which they served, and each director attended 75% or more of such meetings. In addition, in 2021, all of the directors attended the Annual Meeting of Stockholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board of Directors has standing Audit, Compensation, Corporate Governance and Nominating, Finance, and Executive committees. Under the terms of the respective
charters, each member of the Audit, Compensation, and Corporate Governance and Nominating Committees must meet applicable New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) and Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) independence requirements. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Role of Chairman and Chief Executive Officer </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pursuant to the Company&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board examines whether the role of Chairman and CEO should be combined each time the Board elects a
new CEO, and may determine to separate or combine the offices of Chairman and CEO at such other times as it deems appropriate. E. Scott Santi was elected President and CEO in November 2012, and the Board decided to separate the roles of Chairman and
CEO at that time. Given Mr.&nbsp;Santi&#146;s successful transition into the CEO role and his deep knowledge and understanding of the Company&#146;s business model, operations and culture, the Board determined that he was best positioned to lead the
Board in its ongoing oversight of the Company&#146;s operations and strategy. In May 2015, the Board elected Mr.&nbsp;Santi Chairman of the Board and CEO. The Board continues to believe that Mr.&nbsp;Santi is best positioned to lead the Board given
his demonstrated success and quality of leadership. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Strong Independent Lead Director </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Since the roles of Chairman and CEO were combined in 2015, the Board has elected a strong independent director as Lead Director. The Board believes that this structure,
which calls for a strong, independent and highly experienced lead director with well-defined responsibilities, along with the Company&#146;s experienced and engaged independent directors, provides effective oversight of the Company&#146;s
management. Mr.&nbsp;Richard&nbsp;H. Lenny was appointed Lead Director by the Board effective May&nbsp;8, 2020. Mr.&nbsp;Lenny is a highly experienced director who has held several board and management leadership roles and currently serves as <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-executive</FONT> Chairman of the Board of Conagra Brands, Inc. and as a member of the Board of McDonald&#146;s Corporation. In conjunction with the Board&#146;s role in overall strategy and succession planning as
described below, Mr.&nbsp;Lenny actively engages with our Chairman and CEO on such matters. Additionally, Mr.&nbsp;Lenny works closely with our Chairman and CEO on meeting agendas that guide the Board in performing its oversight function, including
with respect to the Company&#146;s strategy and response to the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic, Board succession and Board evaluations. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition to the duties and responsibilities noted above, the Corporate Governance Guidelines state that the Lead Director will: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="9%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">preside at all meetings of the Board at which the chairman is not present, including executive sessions of the independent
directors; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="9%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">act as a key liaison between the chairman and the independent directors; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">11 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board&#146;s Role in Company Strategy and Executive Succession Planning </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board has an active role in the Company&#146;s overall strategies. Each year, the Board conducts a comprehensive, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-depth</FONT>
review of the Company&#146;s long-term strategy and annual operating plan and actively monitors and reviews management&#146;s progress in executing both throughout the year. The Board also conducts an annual review of the Company&#146;s corporate
governance practices. In addition, throughout the year the Board conducts individual segment strategy reviews with segment leadership. The Board also reviews annually the Company&#146;s sustainability strategy and receives periodic updates regarding
the Company&#146;s sustainability initiatives and progress. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board recognizes that one of its most important duties is to ensure continuity in the Company&#146;s
senior leadership by overseeing the development of executive talent and planning for the effective succession of the Company&#146;s CEO and the executive leadership team. In order to ensure that the succession planning and leadership development
process supports and enhances ITW&#146;s strategic objectives, including the Company&#146;s diversity goals, the Board regularly consults with the CEO on the Company&#146;s organizational needs, its leadership pipeline and the succession plans for
critical leadership positions. On an annual basis, the Board conducts a detailed review of executive succession plans, in addition to addressing the Company&#146;s talent management initiatives and discussing individuals who are considered potential
future senior executives of the Company. Similarly, leadership development, including succession planning, is a top priority of the CEO and the senior executive team. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board&#146;s Role in Risk Oversight </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Board of Directors is responsible for the overall risk oversight of the Company with a focus on the most significant risks facing the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board&#146;s
oversight process builds upon management&#146;s annual enterprise risk assessment. The Company has identified key enterprise risks, including, but not limited to, legal/compliance/reputation, controllership/tax, key leader continuity/succession,
supply chain integrity/continuity, cybersecurity, plastics in consumer packaging and significant external event risks. The Board has a formal process to review these risks annually or more frequently, if appropriate. Company management presents on
these risks, at least annually, at meetings of the Company&#146;s Board and Board committees, providing them with an opportunity to discuss the risks and the Company&#146;s risk mitigation processes. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board has delegated to the Audit Committee the responsibility to review and evaluate the Company&#146;s overall financial and compliance risk policies and practices,
including certain legal affairs and environmental, safety and health matters and related policies; has delegated to the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee the responsibility to advise the Board on matters of corporate governance and
associated risks; has delegated to the Finance Committee the responsibility to review and evaluate the risks relating to financings, capital structure, pension obligations, and other treasury functions; and has delegated to the Compensation
Committee the responsibility to review and evaluate the risks arising from the Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices. The Compensation Committee also advises management on whether the Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices
may have a material adverse effect on the Company. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">12 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Throughout 2021, the Board continued to oversee the Company&#146;s strategy and response to the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic, including with respect to the health, safety and financial challenges presented, receiving regular updates from management. Regular access to information provided the Board with opportunities to
effectively exercise its oversight function and provide leadership and support to management during these unprecedented times. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In instances where a particular
committee reviews certain risks, that committee reports on those risks to the full Board on a regular basis. The Company believes that because each of these committees is comprised solely of independent directors, the Chairman and CEO of the Company
is subject to the risk oversight of independent directors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The committee descriptions below provide more detail regarding the risk oversight delegated to each
committee by the Board. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for the integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements, compliance with legal and regulatory requirements, the independence and
performance of ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, and the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. In addition, the Committee is responsible for the oversight and engagement of our independent registered
public accounting firm and assists the Board with respect to matters involving and overseeing accounting, financial reporting, and internal audit functions. In addition, as required by the Company&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines and Audit
Committee charter, the Audit Committee annually reviews legal affairs and environmental, safety and health matters that may have a material impact on the Company&#146;s financial statements or the Company&#146;s compliance policies. The Audit
Committee reviews and evaluates certain of our policies and practices with respect to risk assessment and risk management and steps taken by management to monitor and control such exposures, including with respect to cybersecurity. The Audit
Committee also receives quarterly cybersecurity reports from management. Additional information on the Audit Committee and its activities is set forth under &#147;Audit Committee Report.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Compensation Committee </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation
Committee establishes and oversees the Company&#146;s executive compensation philosophy, programs and policies, including ensuring that executive compensation is aligned with Company and individual performance. The Compensation Committee recommends
to the other independent directors compensation for the chief executive officer, reviews and approves the chief executive officer&#146;s recommendations regarding the compensation of our other executive officers, and makes recommendations regarding
new incentive compensation and equity-based plans or amendments to any existing plans. The Compensation Committee also is responsible for reviewing and evaluating risks arising from our compensation policies and practices and providing input to
management on whether such policies and practices may have a material adverse effect on the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Under its charter, the Compensation Committee may retain an
independent compensation consultant or other advisors. The Compensation Committee engaged independent consultants Frederic W. Cook&nbsp;&amp; Co., Inc. (Cook) until May 2021 and Meridian Compensation Partners LLC (Meridian) beginning in June 2021,
as its independent advisor to review the Company&#146;s overall executive compensation program, review the peer group of companies used by the Compensation Committee for comparison purposes and assess our compensation governance process. Based on
representations from Cook, Meridian and executive officers and directors of the Company, the Compensation Committee has determined that Cook, Meridian and their respective individual compensation advisors to the committee are independent. See
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; How We Make Compensation Decisions &#151; Role of the Compensation Consultant.&#148; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">13 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Additional information on the Compensation Committee, its activities, its relationship with its compensation
consultant and the role of management in setting compensation is provided under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee identifies, evaluates and recommends director candidates; develops, administers and recommends corporate governance
guidelines; reviews and makes recommendations on matters of corporate governance and associated risks; oversees the evaluations of the performance and procedures of the Board and individual directors; makes recommendations as to Board committees and
Board size; and makes a recommendation to the Board regarding the determination of director independence for the Board, the Audit Committee and the Compensation Committee. It is also responsible for reviewing with the Board qualification criteria
for Board members. This committee also oversees and makes recommendations to the independent directors regarding non-employee director compensation. See &#147;Corporate Governance Policies and Practices &#151; Director Candidate Selection
Process&#148; for a description of the director selection process. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Finance Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Finance Committee reviews, evaluates and recommends management&#146;s proposals to the Board relating to the Company&#146;s financings and dividend policy, and
reviews and evaluates an annual summary of the funding and investment status of significant benefit plans sponsored by the Company globally. The Finance Committee also periodically reviews and evaluates the Company&#146;s capital structure and
capital allocation strategy as well as risks arising from the Company&#146;s treasury function. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Executive Committee </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Executive Committee may act on behalf of the Board if a matter requires Board action between meetings of the full Board. The Executive Committee&#146;s authority in
certain matters is limited by law and our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws.</FONT> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Committee Memberships </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the committee memberships effective on May&nbsp;7, 2021 and the number of meetings held by each committee during 2021. </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_8"></A>Corporate Governance Policies and Code of Conduct </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>General </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">One of our core values is integrity, and we have long believed that strong corporate governance is important to assure that the Company is managed for the long-term
benefit of its stockholders. Accordingly, we continuously review our corporate governance policies and practices not only for compliance with applicable laws, the rules and regulations of the SEC, and the listing standards of the NYSE, but also for
strong corporate governance and social and environmental responsibility principles and standards of behavior. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide a framework for the effective governance of the Company and address such
matters as Board structure, Board governance and the responsibilities of the independent Lead Director. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Code of Conduct sets forth standards of conduct applicable to all employees and directors, and all relevant aspects of
our Code of Conduct are also applied to our suppliers through our Supplier Code of Conduct. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Global Anti-Corruption Policy emphasizes the importance of complying with anti-corruption laws of all countries in
which ITW and our divisions, subsidiaries, agents, consultants and affiliates operate. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Code of Ethics sets forth standards of ethical dealing, full and fair disclosure and compliance applicable to our CEO,
Vice Chairman, CFO, and all key financial personnel. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="10%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our Sustainability Report describes our sustainability strategy and our commitment to robust governance and ethics, our
people, our communities and our environment and provides information about our goals and progress in these areas. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit, Compensation and
Corporate Governance and Nominating Committees each review their Committee charters annually and recommend that the Board of Directors approve any changes. Our website (<U>https://investor.itw.com</U>) includes the charters of these committees, the
Company&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Code of Conduct, the Global Anti-Corruption Policy, the Code of Ethics for the Chief Executive Officer and key financial and accounting personnel, and the Sustainability Report, none of which is
incorporated herein by reference. Any amendments to or waivers of the Code of Ethics will be promptly posted on our website. Copies of these documents will be provided, without charge, upon request. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board Independence </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Corporate
Governance and Nominating Committee conducts an annual review and makes a recommendation to the full Board as to whether each of our directors meets the applicable independence standards of the NYSE. In accordance with the NYSE listing standards,
our Board of Directors has adopted categorical standards for director independence, including heightened standards applicable to members of our Audit and Compensation Committees. A copy of the Company&#146;s Categorical Standards for Director
Independence is attached as <B>Appendix A</B>. A director will not be considered independent unless the Board of Directors determines that the director has no material relationship with the Company (directly, or as a partner, stockholder or officer
of an organization that has a material relationship with the Company). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board has determined that, other than E. Scott Santi, each of our current directors has
no material relationship with the Company other than as a director and is independent within the meaning of the </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">15 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
Company&#146;s Categorical Standards for Director Independence and the listing standards of the NYSE. In making its independence determinations, the Board of Directors has broadly considered all
relevant facts and circumstances including that: (1)&nbsp;Ms.&nbsp;Crown and Messrs. Henderson and&nbsp;Smith serve as directors of Northern Trust Corporation and its subsidiary, The Northern Trust Company, with which the Company has a commercial
banking relationship; (2)&nbsp;Messrs. Brutto, Griffith, Henderson and Lenny and Ms.&nbsp;Strobel serve or served as directors of companies that have an existing customer or supplier relationship with the Company; (3)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;David&nbsp;B.
Smith, Jr. is the nephew of Harold B. Smith, emeritus director of the Company; and (4)&nbsp;each of Messrs. Ford and Williams are officers of companies with which we conduct business. The Board has concluded that these relationships are not material
and, therefore, do not impair the independence of these directors or the director nominee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board Evaluations </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board of Directors and the Audit, Compensation, and Corporate Governance and Nominating Committees conduct annual evaluations that assess the effectiveness,
processes, skills, functions and other matters relevant to the Board as a whole or to the particular committee. Results of the evaluations are summarized and discussed at Board and committee meetings. In addition, the Board conducts a peer review
evaluation led by our independent Lead Director, whereby each Board member evaluates the contributions of the other Board members, and each director receives feedback from this peer review from our independent Lead Director. The evaluation process
provides the Board with actionable feedback to enhance its performance and effectiveness. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Qualifications and Succession
Planning </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee periodically reviews with the Board the skills and characteristics required of Board
members in the context of the current <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">make-up</FONT> of the Board and screens and recommends nominees for director to the full Board. Pursuant to our Corporate Governance Guidelines, the criteria for Board membership
includes skills, such as an understanding of manufacturing, marketing, finance, regulation and public policy, international background and experience, age, diversity (including racial, ethnic and gender diversity), and ability to provide strategic
insight and direction on the Company&#146;s key strategic initiatives. In addition to skills and experience, Board candidates are considered based upon various criteria, such as their personal integrity and judgment, global business and social
perspective, and concern for the long-term interests of our stockholders. Although there is no specific policy regarding Board diversity quotas, racial, ethnic and gender diversity are important factors considered in the director selection process.
Of the ten director nominees, two are female and two are African-American men. In addition, directors must have time available to devote to Board activities and to enhance their knowledge of the global manufacturing environment. Accordingly, we seek
to attract and retain a diverse board composed of highly qualified directors who have sufficient time to attend to their duties and responsibilities to the Company. For a chart summarizing the skills and attributes of our director nominees, see
&#147;Corporate Governance Highlights&nbsp;&#151; Composition of Director Nominees.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pursuant to ITW&#146;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, a director may not
stand for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">re-election</FONT> after his or her 75th birthday, except in rare circumstances approved by the Board. The Committee believes it is important to replace skills that may be lost as directors approach
retirement age and to identify skills to supplement existing board experience. The Committee discusses with the full Board its analysis of the characteristics and key attributes for future Board candidates. After receiving recommendations for
nominations from the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, the Board nominates or elects candidates for director. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">16 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Candidate Selection Process </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, or other members of the Board of Directors, may identify a need to add new members to the Board of Directors with
specific skills or to fill a vacancy on the Board. At that time, the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee would initiate a search, seeking input from Board members and senior management and, to the extent it deems appropriate, engaging a
search firm. An initial qualified candidate or a slate of qualified candidates would be identified and presented to the Committee for its evaluation and approval. The Committee would then seek full Board approval of the selected candidate(s). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> permit any stockholder or group of up to 20 stockholders meeting certain ownership requirements to nominate a
director candidate or candidates for inclusion in our proxy statement and form of proxy. For a description of the process for submitting a director candidate through the use of proxy access, see &#147;Other Information &#151; Submitting Proxy
Proposals and Director Nominations for the 2023 Annual Meeting &#151; How do I use proxy access to nominate a director candidate to be included in ITW&#146;s 2023 Proxy Statement?&#148; Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> also permit
stockholders to nominate directors for consideration at an annual meeting of stockholders without requiring that their nominees be included in our proxy statement and form of proxy. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee will consider a
candidate who has been properly nominated pursuant to Article II, Section&nbsp;10 of the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> by following substantially the same process, and applying substantially the same criteria, as for
candidates submitted by other sources, but the Committee has no obligation to recommend that candidate for nomination. For a description of the process for submitting a director candidate without proxy access, see &#147;Other Information &#151;
Submitting Proxy Proposals and Director Nominations for the 2023 Annual Meeting &#151; How do I nominate a director candidate who would not be included in ITW&#146;s Proxy Statement?&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Director Election </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide for the election of directors in uncontested elections by majority vote. Under this majority vote standard, each director must be elected by a majority of the votes cast with respect to that
director. For this purpose, a majority of the votes cast means that the number of shares voted &#147;for&#148; a director exceeds the number of shares voted &#147;against&#148; that director. In a contested election, directors will be elected by a
plurality of the votes represented in person or by proxy at the meeting. An election is contested if the number of nominees exceeds the number of directors to be elected. Whether an election is contested or not is determined ten days in advance of
when we file our definitive proxy statement with the SEC. This year&#146;s election is uncontested, and the majority vote standard will apply. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If a nominee who is
serving as a director is not elected at an annual meeting, Delaware law provides that the director would continue to serve on the Board as a &#147;holdover director&#148; until his or her successor is elected. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines,
however, require any nominee for director who fails to receive a majority of the votes cast for his or her election to tender his or her resignation. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee of the Board will consider the resignation and
recommend to the Board whether to accept or reject it. In considering the resignation, the Committee will take into account such factors as any stated reasons stockholders voted against the election of the director, the length of service and
qualifications of the director, the director&#146;s contributions to the Company, and our Corporate Governance Guidelines. The Board will consider the Committee&#146;s recommendation, but no director who failed to receive a majority of the votes
cast will participate. We will disclose the results of the Committee&#146;s review within 90 days of such annual meeting. At our 2021 Annual Meeting, each director received over 95% of the votes cast for his or her election. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">17 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_9"></A>Shareholder Engagement </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Shareholder Outreach Activities
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe regular, proactive communications with our shareholders to be in the long-term best interests of the Company. Our investor communications
and outreach typically include annual investor day meetings, quarterly conference calls, investor conferences, and analyst meetings and calls throughout the year at the request of investors. These meetings provide a forum to engage with our
shareholders on topics including strategy, financial performance, risk management, talent development, compensation, corporate governance, and social and environmental matters. Management representatives led numerous meetings throughout 2021 on
these topics and sought valuable feedback from our shareholders.</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Additionally, we regularly engage with shareholders holding more than a majority of our shares
regarding environmental, social and governance topics, shareholder proposals and any other topics of interest to our investors, and we share feedback we receive from our investors with our Board. We have received valuable inputs from our investors
related to our progress in executing our sustainability strategy. We have also received supportive feedback regarding Board composition, diversity and inclusion strategies, goals and progress, our response to
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19,</FONT> our greenhouse gas emissions intensity reduction target, and our continuous journey to utilize the SASB Materiality Map<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">&reg;</SUP> and the Task Force on
Climate-related Financial Disclosures (TCFD) framework to guide our sustainability-related disclosures. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As part of our annual investor outreach, early this year we
offered the opportunity to holders of approximately 55% of our shares, represented by 22 investors, to engage with us regarding governance-related matters, the special meeting shareholder proposal, our progress on sustainability and any other topics
they wished to discuss. Eight investors, holding in the aggregate approximately 32% of our shares, engaged with us by telephone. Others indicated that they had no questions and did not feel a call was needed. Overall, the discussions were positive,
with investors expressing support for the Company&#146;s Board, current governance practices and progress in executing our sustainability strategy. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How to Communicate with our Directors </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shareholders and other interested parties may communicate with any of our directors,
including our independent Lead Director, or with the independent directors as a group by sending an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">e-mail</FONT> to <B><U>independentdirectors@itw.com</U></B> or by writing to the independent directors as a group or
to any of our directors c/o Illinois Tool Works Inc., 155 Harlem Avenue, Glenview, IL 60025, Attention: Secretary, with a designation on the outside of the envelope as a &#147;Board Communication.&#148; Relevant communications will be forwarded by
the Secretary to the appropriate directors depending on the facts and circumstances outlined in the communication. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_10"></A>Director Compensation </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT>
directors receive retainer-only compensation with no fees for attending meetings, which is an expected part of Board service. Our committee chairs and Lead Director receive additional retainers for their service in these capacities, and all Board
members receive an annual equity grant based on a fixed-value amount with immediate vesting that avoids entrenchment. Our directors&#146; compensation is compared to that of the same peer group of companies used for executive compensation
comparisons. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">18 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee oversees and makes recommendations to the Board regarding <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director compensation based on comparisons of financial performance and median compensation levels of our peer group. Our 2021 peer group directors&#146; compensation data was prepared by Cook. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Annual Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director compensation for 2021. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> directors are given the opportunity to elect to receive all or a portion of their annual cash retainer,
including chair and Lead Director fees, in an equivalent value of ITW common stock pursuant to our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan. The number of ITW shares to be issued to a director is determined by dividing the dollar amount of the fee subject to
the election by the fair market value of ITW common stock on the date the fee otherwise would have been paid in cash. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Annual Stock Grant</P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="padding-bottom:1pt ;BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> $170,000<P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Directors&#146; Deferred Fee Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> directors can defer receipt of all or a portion of their annual cash retainer, including chair and Lead Director
fees, and/or stock grant until retirement or resignation. Deferred cash amounts are credited with interest quarterly at 120% of the applicable federal long-term rate for the quarter. Cash fees may be deferred as cash or ITW common stock. If a
director elects to defer receipt of any ITW common stock to be received in lieu of a cash payment and/or any portion of his or her stock grant, the deferred shares are credited as stock units to an account in the director&#146;s name. The account
receives share-equivalent credit for cash dividends and is adjusted for stock dividends, splits, combinations or other changes in ITW common stock upon retirement, resignation or a corporate change (as defined in our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan),
with any fractional shares paid in cash. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Common Stock Grant </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company grants stock to its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors under our 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan, which links this element of
compensation to long-term performance. Under our director compensation program, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors serving in 2021 received an annual stock grant equivalent in value to approximately $170,000. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">19 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:1pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Directors and Executive Officers </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the number of shares of ITW common stock beneficially owned by ITW&#146;s executive officers and Board of Directors as of December&nbsp;31,
2021, except as otherwise noted. The &#147;percent of class&#148; calculation is based on 312,905,310 shares of ITW common stock outstanding as of December&nbsp;31, 2021. In general, beneficial ownership includes any shares a director or executive
officer can vote or dispose and stock options, restricted stock units and performance share units </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">20 </P>

(including accrued dividends thereon) that are currently vested or that become vested within 60 days. Except as otherwise noted, the stockholders named in this table have sole voting and
investment power for all shares shown as beneficially owned by them. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The number of the directors&#146; phantom stock units disclosed in the table represents an
equivalent number of shares of ITW common stock as of December&nbsp;31, 2021. Because the granting of phantom stock units was discontinued in May 2012, Messrs.&nbsp;Ford, Henderson and Lenny, who joined the Board after that date, were not awarded
phantom stock units upon joining the Board. Phantom stock units are not transferable and have no voting rights. The units are payable in cash and are not included in the &#147;percent of class&#148; calculation. </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_13"></A>Compensation Discussion and Analysis
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This Compensation Discussion and Analysis provides detailed information about our 2021 compensation programs, policies, and practices, as well as the
principles and philosophy utilized by the Compensation Committee (the Committee) regarding these programs for the named executive officers (NEOs) in the Summary Compensation Table. For 2021, our NEOs are: </P>

<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:12pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD WIDTH="100%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:12pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_14"></A><A NAME="tx236440_101"></A>Executive Overview</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our Business Model </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD WIDTH="61%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="37%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">ITW is a global industrial manufacturing company comprised of seven industry leading segments. In late 2012, we launched our Enterprise Strategy with
the explicit goal of positioning ITW to deliver solid growth with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">best-in-class</FONT></FONT> margins and returns by focusing the entire Company on utilizing our highly differentiated
and proprietary ITW Business Model to its full potential.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ITW Business Model is the core
source of our competitive advantage as a company. It drives our ability to win with customers and deliver differentiated returns for our shareholders. It is a powerful and proprietary set of strategic, operational, and cultural practices that have
been in a state of continual development and evolution inside the Company for over 30 years.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g236440g51a99.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">24 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Our Long-term Enterprise Strategy </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In launching our long-term Enterprise Strategy ten years ago, we began the Company&#146;s transition to fully leverage the compelling performance potential of the ITW
Business Model. The Company undertook a complete review of our performance and began executing a multi-step approach to shift our primary growth engine to organic revenue growth, while delivering <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">best-in-class</FONT></FONT> margins and returns. Key initiatives of our Enterprise Strategy included a portfolio realignment, business structure simplification, strategic sourcing, and diligent <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">re-application</FONT> of ITW&#146;s proprietary 80/20 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Front-to-Back</FONT></FONT> Process to optimize our segments for growth. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Since implementing our Enterprise Strategy in 2012, ITW&#146;s operating margin has increased from 15.9&nbsp;percent to 24.1&nbsp;percent and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">After-tax</FONT> Return on Average Invested Capital <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(After-tax</FONT> ROIC)** has increased from 14.5&nbsp;percent to 29.5&nbsp;percent. Over this same period, we have grown Earnings Per
Share (EPS) by a compound annual growth rate of 11&nbsp;percent, and the Company&#146;s market capitalization has more than tripled. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>2021: Disciplined Execution and Strong Financial Performance in a Challenging Environment </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Throughout 2021, in the face of a very challenging operating environment, we continued to leverage the strength and resilience of the ITW Business Model to deliver for
our customers while responding decisively to rapidly rising raw material costs, continuing to protect the health and well-being of our ITW global colleagues, and aggressively executing our &#145;Win the Recovery&#146; strategy to accelerate
profitable market penetration and organic growth across our portfolio. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">25 </P>

</DIV></Center>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company achieved record EPS of $8.51 in 2021, up 28% from 2020, and up 10% from 2019. Additionally, the Company
delivered very strong financial performance, including: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
