 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">53 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To identify the median employee, we collected employees&#146; regular pay (salary or hourly wages), overtime pay and
shift differentials/premiums, and pay received for paid time off. We did not include annual incentives or bonuses, sales incentives or commissions, long-term cash or equity incentives, allowances, or any benefits received as part of a
company-sponsored defined benefit pension plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">With the information collected, we identified 21 employees whose compensation we believed to be around the median of
all employees, and then gathered other elements of compensation (variable pay, health and welfare, and retirement contributions) in order to determine the final median employee. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The 2021 compensation for the median employee, who we identified in 2020, was $61,011. Total compensation for our CEO, as set forth in the Summary Compensation Table,
plus the Company costs to provide his health and welfare benefits ($19,222) for 2021 was $20,806,844. Accordingly, the pay ratio between our CEO and median employee was 341:1 in 2021. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">54 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_32"></A>Certain Relationships and Related Party
Transactions </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We review related-party transactions in accordance with our Code of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate
Governance Guidelines, rather than a separate written policy. A related-party transaction is a transaction involving the Company and any of the following persons: a director, director nominee or executive officer of the Company; a holder of more
than 5% of ITW common stock; or an immediate family member or person sharing the household of any of these persons. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ITW Code of Conduct states that our
directors, officers and employees must avoid engaging in any activity that might create a conflict of interest or a perception of a conflict of interest. These individuals are required to raise for consideration any proposed or actual transaction
that they believe may create a conflict of interest. Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that no related-party transaction is void or voidable solely because a director has an interest if (1)&nbsp;the material facts are
disclosed to or known by the Board of Directors and the transaction is approved by the disinterested directors or an appropriate Board committee comprised of disinterested directors, (2)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the
stockholders and the transaction is approved by the stockholders, or (3)&nbsp;the transaction is fair to the Company as of the time it is approved. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide that the Board will apply established Categorical
Standards for Director Independence in making its independence determinations. Under the standards, certain relationships between the Company and a director would preclude a director from being considered independent. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On an annual basis, each director, director nominee and executive officer completes a Directors&#146; and Officers&#146; Questionnaire, which requires disclosure of any
transactions with the Company in which he or she, or any member of his or her immediate family, has a direct or indirect material interest. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee reviews the results of these questionnaires and discusses
any related-party transaction disclosed therein. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition, under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible to conduct a reasonable prior review, and
provide oversight, of all material related party transactions for potential conflicts of interest and to approve such transactions only if it determines the transaction is consistent with the interests of the Company and its shareholders. In
reviewing related-party transactions, the Audit Committee considers the factors set forth in our Code of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, as well as other factors, including the
Company&#146;s rationale for entering into the transaction, alternatives to the transaction, whether the transaction is on terms at least as fair to the Company as would be the case were the transaction entered into with a third party, and the
potential for an actual or apparent conflict of interest. No member of the Audit Committee having an interest in a related-party transaction may participate in any decision regarding that transaction. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">55 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_33"></A>Audit Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee of the Board of Directors is composed of five independent directors, as defined in the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange, and the
Board of Directors has determined that all Audit Committee members are &#147;financially literate.&#148; In addition, the Board of Directors has determined that Messrs. Brutto and Henderson meet the Securities and Exchange Commission criteria of
&#147;audit committee financial expert.&#148; The Audit Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors, which was most recently reviewed by the Audit Committee in February 2022. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for providing oversight to the Company&#146;s financial reporting process through periodic meetings with ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accountants, internal auditors and management in order to review accounting, auditing, internal control and financial reporting matters. The Audit Committee is also responsible for assisting the Board in overseeing: (a)&nbsp;the
integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; (b)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (c)&nbsp;the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications, independence and performance;
(d)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s overall risk policies and practices; and (e)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. Company management is responsible for the preparation and integrity of the financial reporting information
and related systems of internal controls. The Audit Committee, in carrying out its role, relies on Company senior management, including senior financial management, and ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following is the report of the Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed
with senior management the audited financial statements of the Company. Management has confirmed to the Audit Committee that the financial statements have been prepared in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. We have also
reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP, ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s financial statements. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with senior management their assertion and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. Management has confirmed to the Audit
Committee that internal controls over financial reporting have been appropriately designed and are operating effectively to prevent or detect any material financial statement misstatements. We have also reviewed and discussed with
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche
LLP the matters required to be discussed by the applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) under which Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP must provide us with additional information regarding the scope and results
of its audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements. This information includes: (1)&nbsp;Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP&#146;s responsibility under generally accepted auditing standards; (2)&nbsp;significant accounting policies;
(3)&nbsp;management judgments and estimates; (4)&nbsp;any significant audit adjustments or internal control matters; (5)&nbsp;any disagreements with management; and (6)&nbsp;any difficulties encountered in performing the audit. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have received from Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP a letter providing the disclosures required by applicable requirements of the PCAOB regarding the independent
accountant&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence with respect to any relationships between Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP and the Company that in its professional judgment may reasonably be thought to bear on
independence. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has discussed its independence with us, and it has confirmed in the letter that, in its professional judgment, it is in a position to serve the Company as its Independent Registered Public Accounting
Firm. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">56 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee also discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and independent registered public
accounting firm the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The Audit Committee meets periodically with the internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm, with and without management present, to discuss the results
of their examinations, their evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on the
reviews and discussions described above, we recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board approved, the inclusion of the audited financial statements in the Company&#146;s Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended
December&nbsp;31, 2021, for filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pamela B. Strobel, Chair </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Daniel J. Brutto </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Darrell L. Ford </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Jay L. Henderson </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">David B. Smith, Jr. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_34"></A>Proposal 2 - Ratification of the Appointment of
Independent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Registered Public Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm retained to
audit ITW&#146;s financial statements. The Audit Committee is also directly involved in the selection of the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s lead engagement partner in conjunction with the mandatory rotation of the lead
engagement partner. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has engaged Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP (Deloitte) to serve as ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm
for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2022. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has been employed to perform this function for the Company since 2002. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Deloitte, the member firms of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, and their respective affiliates (collectively, the Deloitte
Entities) will bill us approximately $10,701,000 for professional services in connection with the 2021 audit, as compared with $10,386,000 for the 2020 audit of the annual financial statements and internal controls. These fees relate to:
(i)&nbsp;the audit of the annual financial statements included in our Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K;</FONT> (ii)&nbsp;the review of the quarterly financial statements included in our Quarterly Reports on Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-Q;</FONT> (iii)&nbsp;the internal controls audit; and (iv)&nbsp;statutory audits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit-Related Fees
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During 2021 and 2020, the Deloitte Entities billed us approximately $30,000 and $45,000, respectively, for audit-related services. These fees relate
to work performed with respect to technical accounting assistance and regulatory filings. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Tax Fees </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These fees include work performed by the Deloitte Entities for 2021 and 2020 with respect to tax compliance services such as assistance in preparing various types of tax
returns globally ($1,453,000 and $1,359,000, respectively) and tax planning services, often related to our restructurings and new tax rules ($896,000 and $931,000, respectively). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>All Other Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There were no fees for
other services rendered by the Deloitte Entities for 2021 and 2020. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-Approval</FONT>
Policies </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has adopted policies and procedures for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related work to be performed by ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. As a part of those procedures, the Audit Committee performs a qualitative analysis of all audit and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> work to be performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. Each year, the Audit Committee receives a detailed list of the types of audit-related and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services to be performed, along with estimated fee amounts. The Audit Committee then reviews and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> audit work and certain categories of tax
and other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services that may be performed. In conducting its analysis, the Audit Committee carefully contemplates the nature of the services to be provided and considers whether such services:
(i)&nbsp;are prohibited under applicable rules; (ii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants auditing their own work; (iii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants performing management functions; (iv)&nbsp;would place our accountants in a position of
acting as an advocate for the Company; or (v)&nbsp;would present a real risk of a conflict of interest or otherwise impair our accountants&#146; independence. The Audit Committee also annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> the
budget for annual GAAP, statutory and benefit </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">58 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
plan audits. Company management provides quarterly updates to the Audit Committee regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-to-date</FONT></FONT>
expenditures versus budget for audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services. The Audit Committee also considers whether specific projects or expenditures could potentially affect the independence of ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accounting firm. Company management and the independent registered public accounting firm will monitor the fees for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> services on an
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">on-going</FONT> basis to ensure that the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> fees are not exceeded. Company management and the independent registered public accounting firm will seek <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> from the Audit Committee if fees are expected to be incurred for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> services in excess of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT>
amounts. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Any new services and fees are presented to the Audit Committee for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> at each Audit Committee meeting. If
the timing of a new service or fee occurs <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-between</FONT> Audit Committee meetings, a description of the services and fees is provided to the Audit Committee Chair for
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval,</FONT> and any such <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approvals</FONT> are discussed with the full Audit Committee at the next scheduled meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee annually reviews Deloitte&#146;s independence and performance in determining whether to retain Deloitte or engage another firm as our independent
registered public accounting firm. In the course of these reviews, the Audit Committee considers, among other things: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

stockholders to retain Deloitte to serve as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2022. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Although we are not required to do so, we believe that it is
appropriate for us to request stockholder ratification of the appointment of Deloitte as our independent registered public accounting firm. If stockholders do not ratify the appointment, the Audit Committee will investigate the reasons for the
stockholders&#146; rejection and reconsider the appointment. Representatives of Deloitte will be present at our Annual Meeting and will have the opportunity to make a statement and respond to questions. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP. </B></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_35"></A>Proposal 3 - Advisory Vote on Executive
Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In accordance with the recommendation by the Board and the preference expressed by our stockholders at the 2017 Annual Meeting, the Company
has an advisory vote on executive compensation annually. The Company is seeking your advisory vote on our executive compensation, as disclosed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section, the compensation tables and any related
material disclosed in this proxy statement pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules. The Compensation Committee will review the voting results and take them into consideration when making future decisions regarding executive
compensation, but because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding on the Compensation Committee, the Board or the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that our executive
compensation program is competitive and strongly aligned with our strategic performance goals and the long-term interests of our stockholders. Our compensation program and structure are more fully described in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&#148; and &#147;NEO Compensation&#148; sections of this proxy statement. We encourage you to closely review this information before voting on the compensation we paid to our NEOs in 2021. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We ask our stockholders to approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of our NEOs by voting &#147;FOR&#148; the following resolution: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:13%; margin-right:13%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Resolved: </B>that the compensation of the named executive officers of Illinois Tool Works Inc. (the Company) as disclosed pursuant
to the compensation disclosure rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; in the Summary Compensation Table, the related compensation tables and the related narrative disclosures in the
Company&#146;s proxy statement for its 2022 Annual Meeting, is hereby approved. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote &#147;FOR&#148; the
approval of the compensation of </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the Company&#146;s named executive officers. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">60 </P>

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_36"></A>Proposal 4 -
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal to Change the </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Ownership Threshold to
Call Special Stockholder Meetings </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has been notified that John Chevedden intends to present the following proposal for consideration at the
Annual Meeting. The Company will provide Mr.&nbsp;Chevedden&#146;s address and the number of shares of ITW&#146;s common stock held by him upon oral or written request made to our Corporate Secretary. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You should read carefully the description of the proposal. The Board of Directors recommends that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Stockholder Proposal and Supporting Statement </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Proposal 4 &#150; Special Shareholder Meeting Improvement </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shareholders ask our board to take the steps necessary to amend the appropriate company governing documents to give the owners of a combined 10% of our outstanding
common stock the power to call a special shareholder meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">One of the main purposes of this proposal is to give shareholders the right to formally participate in
calling for a special shareholder meeting regardless of their length of stock ownership to the fullest extent possible. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">It currently takes a theoretical 20% of
shares to call a special shareholder meeting. This theoretical 20% of shares translates into 25% of shares that normally vote at the annual meeting. It would be hopeless to think that the shares, that do not have the time to vote, would go out of
their way to take the procedural steps to call for a special shareholder meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Plus Illinois Tool shareholders do not have a related right for shareholders to
act by written consent. Many companies provide for both a shareholder right to call a special meeting and for a shareholder right to act by written consent. Target and Southwest Airlines are companies that do not provide for shareholder written
consent and yet provide for 10% of shares to call for a special shareholder meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">ITW shareholders gave 36%-support to a written consent proposal at the 2021
annual meeting. This 36% support likely equaled 40%+ support from the shares that have access to independent proxy voting advice. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Conagra shareholders gave
85%-support to a 2021 shareholder proposal for a shareholder right to act by written consent. This 85%-support was all the more impressive since the shareholder proponent did nothing to promote his proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Special meetings allow shareholders to vote on important matters, such as electing new directors with special expertise or independence that may be lacking in our
current or future directors. This was the case with the 3 new Exxon directors supported by the Engine No.&nbsp;1 hedge fund at the 2021 Exxon annual meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">Please vote yes: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Special Shareholder Meeting
Improvement &#151; Proposal 4 </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">


<IMG SRC="g236440g01a60.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">61 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board of Directors Statement in Opposition </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">After careful consideration, and informed by dialogue with our stockholders on this topic, the Board believes the shareholder proposal to lower the threshold for holders
of our common stock to call a special meeting is not in the best interests of ITW and its stockholders. The Board therefore recommends a vote AGAINST the proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Company has a track record of strong corporate governance. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company is committed to sound corporate governance and has
implemented numerous corporate governance policies and practices that ensure accountability of the Board to our stockholders and provide our stockholders with access to the Board. As a result of these structural governance practices, stockholders
have meaningful, year-round opportunities to bring important matters to the attention of the Company, the Board and other stockholders, which we believe is the reason our stockholders rejected this proponent&#146;s proposal to lower the threshold to
call a special meeting in 2018 as well as his proposals for action by written consent in 2017, 2019, 2020 and 2021. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For example: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">We have an actively engaged independent Lead Director; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">We have a director resignation policy for directors who fail to receive the required majority vote; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">We have an anti-hedging and anti-pledging policy; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">We have a compensation recovery (clawback) policy; and </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">We do not have a poison pill. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We view our relationship with our stockholders as fundamental to good corporate governance practices. As part of our robust corporate governance, we regularly monitor
developments in corporate governance and solicit feedback on governance practices during our ongoing engagement with stockholders. We continually evaluate stockholder feedback and developments in corporate governance and implement appropriate
changes to our corporate governance policies and practices when they are in the best interests of the Company and our stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>The
Current 20% Ownership Threshold is Reasonable and More Favorable to Stockholders than the Majority of S&amp;P 500 Companies </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Certificate of
Incorporation and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that any person or persons holding at least 20% of the Company&#146;s common stock outstanding may call a special meeting upon written request to our
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">62 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
secretary. The Board believes that this 20% threshold is reasonable, appropriate and aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests. In fact, the current threshold of 20% is more
stockholder-friendly than the vast majority of S&amp;P 500 companies, approximately 70% of which either have no right to call a special meeting or have a special meeting threshold of 25% or higher. When adopting the current threshold, the Board
considered stockholder input and determined that the 20% threshold struck the appropriate balance between assuring that stockholders have the ability to call a special meeting and protecting against the risk that a small minority of our
stockholders, including those with special interests, could trigger the expense and distraction of a special meeting for reasons that may not be in the best interests of the Company or all of our stockholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that a special shareholder meeting should be convened only to discuss extraordinary events when fiduciary, strategic or similar considerations dictate the
matter be addressed prior to the next annual meeting. Convening a special meeting imposes substantial legal, administrative and distribution costs and requires a significant commitment of time and focus from the Company&#146;s Board and senior
management, distracting them from their primary focus of maximizing long-term financial returns and operating our business in the best interests of stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B>Adoption of a 10% Threshold Could Allow a Small Number of Stockholders to Call a Special Meeting to Pursue Their Narrow Interests at the Expense of All Stockholders. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A 10% threshold is not in the best interests of ITW&#146;s stockholders. A threshold that low could permit a small group of stockholders to use the extraordinary measure
of calling a special meeting to serve the group&#146;s narrow self-interests at the expense of the vast majority of the stockholders and the Company. For example, event-driven hedge funds or other activists could pursue a special meeting with the
goal of disrupting our business or proposing issues that facilitate their own short-term aims. This concern is heightened if such stockholders can borrow shares from other stockholders for the sole purpose of meeting the required threshold necessary
to call a special meeting. Based on our stockholder base over the last several years, just two stockholders could constitute a 10% group. The Board believes that a 20% threshold ensures that a meaningful percentage of our stockholders agree on the
need for a special meeting before a special meeting is called. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our stockholders&#146; right to vote on significant matters is already protected by state law and
other regulations. As a Delaware corporation, ITW is required to have all major corporate actions, such as mergers, a sale of all or substantially all of our assets or increases or decreases in authorized shares, approved by stockholders. As a New
York Stock Exchange listed company, ITW is also required to obtain shareholder approval for, among other things, equity compensation plans, significant issuances of securities to related parties and issuances representing more than 20% of the
Company&#146;s voting power. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We engage regularly with our stockholders regarding our corporate governance and believe that most of them agree that the current 20%
threshold is appropriate. At ITW&#146;s 2015 annual meeting, the Board recommended in favor of a stockholder proposal to adopt a special meeting provision at a 20% ownership threshold, which was supported by the vast majority of our stockholders. In
2018, 62% of our stockholders voted against a proposal to lower that ownership threshold to 10%. We will continue to seek our stockholders&#146; input on this and other topics and will consider such input as we continually review our corporate
governance policies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In light of the strong stockholder rights in place, including the right for stockholders of 20% of our outstanding shares to call a special
meeting, and the Board&#146;s demonstrated commitment to good governance practices, the Board believes that adoption of this proposal is not necessary and could permit the special interests of a small group of stockholders to exert undue influence
and disrupt the Company&#146;s operations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>For the foregoing reasons, the Board of Directors believes this proposal is not in </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the best interests of the Company or our stockholders and unanimously recommends </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>a vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; this proposal. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">63 </P>

</DIV></Center>

ITW common stock that you own entitles you to one vote. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I vote? </I></B></FONT></P>

you call or go to <U>www.proxyvote.com</U>. If you hold your shares through a bank or broker that does not offer telephone or Internet voting, please complete and return your proxy voting instruction card by mail. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>When must I submit my vote by Internet or by phone? </I></B></FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>If I hold shares through an ITW Savings and Investment 401(k) Plan, when must I submit my vote? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shares held through an ITW 401(k) plan must be voted by 10:59 p.m., Central Time, on May&nbsp;3, 2022. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">64 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I attend the Annual Meeting? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Annual Meeting will be held in virtual format to protect the health of our stockholders and directors during the continuing
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">COVID-19</FONT> pandemic and to make the Annual Meeting accessible to all of our stockholders. The virtual Annual Meeting will afford our stockholders the same rights and opportunities as an <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">in-person</FONT> meeting, allowing for active participation by all our stockholders at no cost, regardless of their geographic location. To attend the Annual Meeting, vote and submit questions during the Annual Meeting, go
to <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> on the date of the meeting. If you are a registered stockholder or beneficial owner of common stock holding shares at the close of business on the record date, you may attend the Annual Meeting,
examine our list of stockholders, vote and submit questions by visiting <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> and logging in by entering the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number found on your proxy card, Notice
of Internet Availability or voter instruction card, as applicable. If you lost or misplaced your <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number or are not a stockholder, you will be able to attend the meeting as a guest by visiting
<U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> and registering as a guest. If you enter the meeting as a guest, you will not be able to examine our list of stockholders, vote your shares or submit questions during the meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You may log into the Annual Meeting beginning at 8:15 a.m., Central Time, on May&nbsp;6, 2022 and the Annual Meeting will begin promptly at 8:30 a.m., Central Time. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How can I vote my shares at the virtual Annual Meeting? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shares held directly in your name as the stockholder of record may be voted if you are attending the virtual Annual Meeting by entering the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number found on your proxy card or Notice of Internet Availability when you log into the meeting at <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting/ITW2022</U>. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shares held in street name through a brokerage account or by a broker, bank or other nominee may be voted at the virtual Annual Meeting by entering the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number found on your voter instruction card when you log into the meeting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Even if you plan to virtually attend
the Annual Meeting, we recommend that you vote in advance, as described above under &#147;How do I vote?&#148; so that your vote will be counted if you later decide not to attend the Annual Meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>May I ask questions at the virtual Annual Meeting? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Yes. Stockholders (other than those stockholders who enter the meeting as a guest, as described above) will have the ability to submit questions in writing during the
Annual Meeting via the annual meeting portal at <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U>. As part of the Annual Meeting, we will hold a live question and answer session, during which we intend to answer questions submitted during the meeting
that are pertinent to the Company and the business of the meeting, as time permits. Rules of Conduct for the Annual Meeting, including the types of questions that the Company does not intend to address will be available on our website at
<U>https://investor.itw.com</U> prior to the meeting, and on the meeting portal at <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U>, on the day of the meeting. Examples of questions that are not pertinent are questions related to general economic,
political or other views that are not directly related to the business of the Annual Meeting, questions related to personal grievances and derogatory references to individuals. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If there are pertinent questions that cannot be answered during the Annual Meeting due to time constraints, we will post answers to a representative set of such
questions (e.g., consolidating duplicative questions) on our website at <U>https://investor.itw.com</U>. The questions and answers will be made available as soon as practicable after the Annual Meeting. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">65 </P>

</DIV></Center>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What if I have technical difficulties or trouble accessing the virtual Annual Meeting?
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you experience any technical difficulties accessing the virtual Annual Meeting or during the meeting, please call the toll-free number that will
be available at <U>www.virtualshareholdermeeting.com/ITW2022</U> for assistance. We will have technicians ready to assist you with any technical difficulties you may have beginning 15 minutes prior to the start of the Annual Meeting, at 8:15 a.m.,
Central Time, on May&nbsp;6, 2022. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How can I obtain an additional proxy card or voting instruction card? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you lose, misplace or otherwise need to obtain a proxy card, Notice of Internet Availability or voting instruction card and: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">You are the beneficial owner of shares held indirectly through a broker, bank or other nominee, contact your account
representative at that organization<I>.</I> </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How does discretionary voting authority apply? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Stockholders of Record.</I> If you are a stockholder of record and you vote by proxy, the individuals named on the proxy card (your proxies) will vote your shares in
the manner you indicate. If your proxy card does not indicate how you want to vote, your proxy will be voted as follows: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the election of each
director nominee; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the ratification of the appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for
2022; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; the approval of ITW&#146;s executive compensation; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;AGAINST&#148; the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</FONT> stockholder proposal to change the ownership threshold to call special stockholder meetings;
and </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">&#147;FOR&#148; or &#147;AGAINST&#148; any other properly raised matter at the discretion of Susan Crown, Richard H. Lenny and Pamela B. Strobel, or any one of
them. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Beneficial Owners.</I> If your shares are held in a brokerage account or by a nominee and you do not provide your broker or nominee with voting
instructions, the broker or nominee may represent your shares at the meeting for purposes of obtaining a quorum, but it may not exercise discretion to vote your shares at the meeting unless the proposal is considered a routine matter. The only
matter being proposed for stockholder vote at the 2022 Annual Meeting that is considered a routine matter is the proposal to ratify the appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2022. As a
result, in the absence of voting instructions from you, your broker or nominee will not have discretion to vote on any other matter to be voted on at the Annual Meeting. If you are a beneficial owner, it is important that you provide instructions to
your bank, broker or other holder of record so that your vote is counted. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>May I revoke my proxy? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You may revoke your proxy at any time before it is voted at our Annual Meeting in one of four ways: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Notify our Secretary in writing before our Annual Meeting that you wish to revoke your proxy; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Submit another proxy with a later date; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">66 </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vote by telephone or Internet after you have given your proxy; or </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Vote at our virtual Annual Meeting. See &#147;How can I vote my shares at the virtual Annual Meeting?&#148; above. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Why didn&#146;t I receive a paper copy of the proxy statement and Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K?</FONT> </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Unless our stockholders have requested paper copies, we are furnishing proxy materials through the Internet. If you received a Notice of Internet Availability by mail or
electronically, you will not receive a printed copy of the proxy materials unless you specifically request one. Instead, the Notice of Internet Availability provides instructions on how you may access and review our proxy materials online. The
Notice of Internet Availability also instructs you on how you may submit your proxy via the Internet. If you received the Notice of Internet Availability and would still like to receive a printed copy of our proxy materials without charge, you
should follow the instructions for requesting such materials included in the Notice of Internet Availability. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>I have received paper
copies&#151;how do I receive future proxy materials electronically? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To sign up to receive stockholder communications electronically, follow the
instructions on your proxy card or Notice of Internet Availability under &#147;Vote by Internet.&#148; You will need the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number that is printed in the box marked by the arrow, which appears on
your proxy card or Notice of Internet Availability. In order to receive the communications electronically, you must have an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">e-mail</FONT> account and access to the Internet. If you own your shares through a broker or
other nominee, you may contact them directly to request electronic access. Your consent to electronic access will be effective until you revoke it. You may revoke your consent by going to <U>www.proxyvote.com</U> and using the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number that is printed in the box marked by the arrow&nbsp;to complete the revocation. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What does it mean if I receive more than one Notice of Internet Availability or set of proxy materials? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Your shares are likely registered differently or are in more than one account. For each notice, proxy and/or voting instruction card or
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">e-mail</FONT> notification you receive that has a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16-digit</FONT> control number, you must vote each separately to ensure that all shares you own are voted. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I obtain a separate set of proxy materials if I share an address with other stockholders? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have adopted a procedure approved by the SEC called &#147;householding&#148; whereby we are delivering one Notice of Internet Availability or one set of proxy
materials to certain stockholders who share an address, unless otherwise requested. If you received your proxy materials by mail, a separate proxy card is included together the proxy materials for each stockholder sharing an address. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you share an address with another stockholder and received only one set of proxy materials, and would like to request a separate copy of these materials, please
contact Broadridge Financial Solutions, Inc. at <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">1-866-540-7095</FONT></FONT></FONT> or in writing at Broadridge, Householding Department, 51 Mercedes
Way, Edgewood, New York 11717. We will promptly deliver a separate copy (free of charge) upon request. Similarly, if you are eligible for householding, but you and other stockholders of record with whom you share an address currently receive
multiple copies of the Notice of Internet Availability or, if applicable, the proxy materials, or if you hold stock in more than one account, and in either case you wish to receive only a single copy of each of these documents for your household,
you may also contact Broadridge Financial Solutions, Inc. If your shares are held through a brokerage account, please contact your broker directly. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stockholders who
participate in householding will continue to receive separate proxy cards to vote their shares if they receive your proxy materials by mail. Stockholders that receive the Notice of Internet Availability will receive instructions on how to vote their
shares via the Internet. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">67 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What constitutes a quorum? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The presence, in person or by proxy, of the holders of a majority of ITW shares of common stock entitled to vote at our Annual Meeting constitutes a quorum. Your shares
will be considered part of the quorum if you return a signed and dated proxy card or if you vote by telephone or Internet. Abstentions and broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-votes</FONT> are counted as &#147;shares present&#148; at the
meeting for purposes of determining if a quorum exists. A broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-vote</FONT> occurs when your bank, broker or other holder of record holding shares for you as the beneficial owner submits a proxy that does not
indicate a vote as to a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-routine</FONT> proposal because that holder has not received voting instructions from you and, therefore, does not have voting authority for that proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What vote is required to approve each proposal, assuming a quorum is present? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Election of Directors:</I></B>&nbsp;The number of shares voted &#147;FOR&#148; a director must exceed the number of shares voted &#147;AGAINST&#148; that director
to constitute approval by the stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Ratification of the Appointment of our Independent Registered Public Accounting Firm:</I></B>&nbsp;The affirmative
vote of a majority of the shares present in person or by proxy at the Annual Meeting and entitled to vote will constitute approval by the stockholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Advisory <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(Non-Binding)</FONT> Vote on ITW&#146;s Executive Compensation:</I></B>&nbsp;The affirmative vote of a majority of the
shares present in person or by proxy at the Annual Meeting and entitled to vote will constitute approval by the stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><I>Approval of <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal to change the ownership threshold to call special stockholder meetings: </I></B>The affirmative vote of a majority of the shares present in person or by proxy at the Annual Meeting
and entitled to vote will constitute approval by the stockholders. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What is the effect of a broker
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-vote</FONT> generally and on each proposal? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-vote</FONT> occurs
when a broker or other nominee does not receive voting instructions from the beneficial owner and does not have the discretion to direct the voting of the shares. Broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-votes</FONT> will be counted for purposes
of calculating whether a quorum is present at the Annual Meeting, but they will not be counted for purposes of determining the number of votes present in person or represented by proxy and entitled to vote with respect to a particular proposal.
Broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-votes</FONT> will not, therefore, impact our ability to obtain a quorum and will have no effect on the election of directors, ratification of the appointment of our Independent Registered Public Accounting
Firm, approval of ITW&#146;s executive compensation, or approval of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>What if I &#147;abstain&#148; from voting? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">An abstention on the election of directors will have no effect on the outcome. An
abstention on the other proposals will have the effect of a vote against those proposals. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Who pays to prepare, mail and solicit the
proxies? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We will pay the cost of solicitation of proxies including preparing, printing and mailing this proxy statement and the Notice of Internet
Availability. We will also authorize brokers, dealers, banks, voting trustees and other nominees and fiduciaries to forward copies of the proxy materials to the beneficial owners of ITW common stock. Upon request, we will reimburse them for their
reasonable expenses. Also, for a fee of $24,000 plus approved <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">out-of-pocket</FONT></FONT> expenses, Alliance Advisors, LLC assisted us with our shareholder engagement process and may
assist us in soliciting proxies. In addition, our officers, directors and employees may solicit proxies in person, by mail, by telephone or otherwise. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">68 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_39"></A>Submitting Proxy Proposals and Director Nominations for the 2023
Annual Meeting </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I submit a stockholder proposal for the 2023 Annual Meeting? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To be considered for inclusion in our proxy statement for our May 2023 Annual Meeting, a stockholder proposal must be received no later than November&nbsp;25, 2022. Your
proposal must be in writing and must comply with the proxy rules of the SEC. You should send your proposal to our Secretary at our address on the Notice of Annual Meeting of Stockholders immediately following the cover of this proxy statement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You also may submit a proposal that you do not want included in the proxy statement, but that you want to raise at our 2023 Annual Meeting. We must receive your proposal
in writing on or after January&nbsp;6, 2023, but no later than February&nbsp;5, 2023. As detailed in the advance notice procedures described in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws,</FONT> for a proposal other than the nomination of a
director to be properly brought before an annual meeting, your notice of proposal must include: (1)&nbsp;your name and address, as well as the name and address of the beneficial owner of the shares, if any; (2)&nbsp;the number of shares of ITW stock
owned beneficially and of record by you and any beneficial owner as of the date of the notice (which information must be supplemented as of the record date); (3)&nbsp;a description of certain agreements, arrangements or understandings entered into
by you or any beneficial owner with respect to the shares (which information must be supplemented as of the record date) or the business proposed to be brought before the meeting; (4)&nbsp;any other information regarding you or any beneficial owner
that would be required under the SEC&#146;s proxy rules and regulations; and (5)&nbsp;a brief description of the business you propose to be brought before the meeting, the reasons for conducting that business at the meeting, and any material
interest that you or any beneficial owner has in that business. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Does ITW allow stockholders to have proxy access for the nomination of
directors? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Yes. The Board has adopted proxy access <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-law</FONT> provisions to permit stockholders to include
nominees in the Company&#146;s proxy statement and form of proxy. See &#147;How do I use proxy access to nominate a director candidate to be included in ITW&#146;s 2023 Proxy Statement?&#148; below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I use proxy access to nominate a director candidate to be included in ITW&#146;s 2023 Proxy Statement? </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Any stockholder or group of up to 20 stockholders meeting our continuous ownership requirement of 3% or more of our common stock for at least 3 years, who wishes to
nominate a candidate or candidates for election in connection with our 2023 Annual Meeting and require us to include such nominees in our proxy statement and form of proxy, must submit such nomination and request so that it is received by our
Secretary on or after January&nbsp;6, 2023, but no later than February&nbsp;5, 2023. The number of candidates that may be so nominated is limited to the greater of two or the largest whole number that does not exceed 25% of the Board. Recallable
loaned shares count as owned for purposes of meeting the continuous ownership requirement, but each stockholder in the requesting group must have full voting and investment rights as well as economic interest in their shares at the time of
nomination, record date and meeting date. Two or more investment funds that are part of the same family of funds or sponsored by the same employer will count as one stockholder for purposes of determining the size of the group. All proxy access
nominations must be accompanied by information about the nominating stockholders as well as the nominees and meet the requirements as specified in Article II, Section&nbsp;12 of our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws,</FONT> which include but
are not limited to the information specified under &#147;How do I nominate a director candidate who would not be included in ITW&#146;s Proxy Statement?&#148; below. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">69 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>How do I nominate a director candidate who would not be included in ITW&#146;s Proxy
Statement? </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If you wish to nominate an individual for election as a director at our 2023 Annual Meeting, our Secretary must receive your written
nomination on or after January&nbsp;6, 2023, but no later than February&nbsp;5, 2023. As detailed in the advance notice procedures described in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws,</FONT> for a nomination to be properly brought before an
annual meeting, your notice of nomination must include: (1)&nbsp;your name and address, as well as the name and address of the beneficial owner of the shares, if any; (2)&nbsp;the number of shares of ITW stock owned beneficially and of record by you
and any beneficial owner as of the date of the notice (which information must be supplemented as of the record date); (3)&nbsp;a description of certain agreements, arrangements or understandings entered into by you or any beneficial owner with
respect to the shares (which information must be supplemented as of the record date); (4)&nbsp;the name, age and home and business addresses of the nominee; (5)&nbsp;the principal occupation or employment of the nominee; (6)&nbsp;the number of
shares of ITW stock that the nominee beneficially owns; (7)&nbsp;a statement that the nominee is willing to be nominated and serve as a director; (8)&nbsp;a statement as to whether the nominee, if elected, intends to tender his or her resignation to
address majority voting in accordance with our Corporate Governance Guidelines; (9)&nbsp;an undertaking to provide any other information required to determine the eligibility of the nominee to serve as an independent director or that could be
material to stockholders&#146; understanding of the nominee&#146;s independence; and (10)&nbsp;any other information regarding you, any beneficial owner or the nominee that would be required under the SEC&#146;s proxy rules and regulations had our
Board of Directors nominated the individual. Any nomination that you make must be approved by our Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee, as well as by our Board of Directors. The process for the selection of director candidates is described
under &#147;Proposal 1 &#151; Election of Directors &#151; Corporate Governance Policies and Practices &#151; Director Candidate Selection Process.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In
addition to satisfying the foregoing requirement under our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws,</FONT> to comply with the universal proxy rules (once effective), stockholders who intend to solicit proxies in support of director nominees other
than the Company&#146;s nominees must provide notice that sets forth the information required by Rule <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">14a-19</FONT> of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended, no later than March&nbsp;7, 2023. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom236440_40"></A>Forward-Looking Statements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

Such&nbsp;risks&nbsp;include those contained in ITW&#146;s Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2021&nbsp;and other documents ITW files with the SEC.&nbsp;These risks are not <FONT
